~ start

~ first_breakfast
#do Global.player_deparent_camera()
#do CutsceneManager.move_to("malachai", "IM0", "walk", true)
#do CutsceneManager.play_animation("malachai", "idle_left", true)

Cora: [do CutsceneManager.move_to("cora", "C1", "walk", true)] I'm so excited! I always knew Bailey would be back some day! You can take the girl out of Ithaca, but Ithaca always calls her home!

do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "right") # should turn right
Aiden's Dad [i](from other room)[/i]: She never shoulda left, Cora!
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "Samwell") # should turn left
Cora: Samwell! You know they had a bad time over her place!
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "up")  # should turn up
#[do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Samwell", "MPSamwell1",200)]
Samwell: Coulda come stayed with us, Cora.
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", Vector2(200,138)): # should turn left
Cora: Not like we got a lot of room, Samwell.
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "Aiden") # should turn down
Samwell: The child could sleep with the chickens. [i]::to Aiden::[/i] Right, child?
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "Bailey") # should turn down_right
Cora: [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Aiden", "MPAiden1", 200)] That "child" is a half head taller than you, O Lord o' the Manor.
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "down")   # should turn down
Samwell: That's only 'cause I've shrunk with age. A fella reaches a certain level o' dignity, he can let the body deflate a little.
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "up")   # should turn down
Cora: You ain't deflated, the inflation just moved to your middle!
do GI.get_csm().face_target("Cora", "Samwell")   # should turn down_right
Cora: This is filler text!
Aiden: [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Bailey", "MPBailey0",200)] Can the two of you stop the bickering before she gets here?
Bailey: [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Bailey", "MPBailey1",200)] Are you kidding? This isn't bickering, this is love and I've missed hearing it it every day I've been gone!
Cora: [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Ira", "MPIra1",200)] Bailey! You're just in time. The apple skillet's still warm.
Bailey: [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Bailey", "MPBailey2",200)] I wouldn't miss it for the world, Cora.
[do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Cora", "MPCora2",200)] [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Samwell", "MPSamwell2",50)]
Cora: We missed you so much!
do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Aiden", "MPAiden2", 200)
Samwell: [i]::grumbles::[/i] Should've stayed with us, girl.
Bailey: [i]::laughs::[/i] And miss out on the big city? I think not, Samwell.
Aiden: [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Ira", "MPIra2",200)] [next] [i]::grinning::[/i] Bailey's seen more than just chickens and apple skillets, Dad.
Bailey: [i]::glances at Ira::[/i] Oh, and this is Ira. They're my traveling companion.
Ira: [i]::nervously::[/i] The... the skillet smells really good, Mrs. Cora.
Cora: Oh, you're a grownup, dear, it's Cora! And help yourself!
Ira: Thank you, Cora!
[do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Ira", "MPIra3",200)] [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Samwell", "MPSamwell3",50)] [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Cora", "MPCora3",50)] [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Bailey", "MPBailey3",50)] [do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Aiden", "MPAiden3", 50)]
do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Aiden", "MPAiden4", 200)
::They all start eating::
[do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Samwell", "MPSamwell3",200)] [next]
Bailey: [i]::mouth full::[/i] This is just as good as I remember.
Samwell: City didn't teach you any manners, girl?
Bailey: [i]::laughs::[/i] I'm afraid not, Samwell. Some things never change.
Aiden: And we wouldn't have it any other way.
Cora: [i]::laughs::[/i] You always were my biggest fan, Bailey.
Aiden: Only when it comes to your cooking, Mom.
Cora: [i]::laughs::[/i] Well, I'll take what I can get!
Cora: So... Ira... are you JUST a "traveling" companion, or...
Ira: ...
Bailey: ...
Aiden: And you thought I'D said something awkward!
Bailey: [i]::laughs::[/i] I guess you don't get it from the wind!
Bailey: Cora, Ira is a friend, and traveling companion. We've a lot of friends in common in Iris, and when I said I was coming home, they had to come along and see, for some reason.
Ira: Oh, I just had to meet all the people from the stories Bailey's been telling me. And see all the sights!
Cora: ... [wait = 0.5] [next]
Samwell: ... [wait = 0.5] [next]
Aiden: ... [wait = 0.5] [next]
Samwell: [b]SIGHTS?[/b] In [b]ITHACA[/b]?
Ira: Oh, yes! The bridge where Aiden once helped that lost traveler find their way! [wait = 1] [next]
Ira: The old oak tree where the two of you renewed your vows before the entire village! [wait = 1] [next]
Ira: The haystack where Aiden hid that bottle of brandy the summer they were 14!
Samwell and Cora: [b]The WHAT?![/b]
Bailey: Um... That... would have been one of the ones you didn't want your mother to find out about...
Ira: Oh. Um. I'm sorry! But... that was a long time ago and... and they were such wonderful memories that Bailey told me about, and I had to come see them, and meet you all.
Samwell: Well, it's not every day someone comes from the big city to meet us glamorous farm folk. It was good to meet you, Ira, and Bailey, you're always welcome. But now I have to go out and get to work.
Samwell: ...
Samwell: Checking the haystacks.
[do GI.get_csm().start_npc_movement("Samwell", "MPSamwell4",50)]

Aiden: [i]::blushes::[/i]
Bailey and Cora: [i]::burst out laughing::[/i]
Cora: I have work to get to as well. Aiden, I'll need to back to help around here come noon, why don't you run off and play with your friends until then?
#do Global.player_reparent_camera()




=> END

~ snippet
do Global.player_deparent_camera()
Aiden: This is a test
Bailey: What kind of test?
Aiden: A test of the camera reparenting function.

do Global.player_reparent_camera()

~ big_hill
Ira: Oh. [wait=0.5] My. [wait=0.5] ZEE! [wait=1] [next]
Ira: This is the hilltop where the two of you used to watch the stars!
Ira: Aiden would make up stories about the constellations! Like the one about the evil angels filling the sky with black fire!
Aiden: I, ah... I think you might remember it better than I do.
Ira: Oh, Bailey's the one with the memory! I just remember her telling me about it! And I don't tell it nearly as well! [next]
Ira: HEY! Is that... is that a SQUIRREL!? I've always wanted to see a squirrel! [i]::runs off::[/i]
Aiden: So...
Aiden: They seem nice.
Bailey: They ARE! They're just a little...
- Aiden: Awkward?
	Bailey: Sheltered.
	Bailey: But yes, that too.
- Aiden: Annoying?
	Bailey: Sheltered.
	Bailey: I guess they can be annoying too but they don't mean it.
- Aiden: Stupid?
	Bailey: Sheltered.
	Bailey: They're actually quite brilliant. Just not at knowing how to talk to people.
Aiden: How can someone from Iris be so sheltered? I thought the city was where life and death things happened every day.
Bailey: Life and death things happen everywhere every day.
Bailey: It's... a complicated place. Ira's family was very protective. Didn't want them to ever be hurt, so they were very careful who they got to talk to.
Aiden: They must be rich.
Bailey: They are. Or... were.
Aiden: Not anymore?
Bailey: It's not really my story to tell. You can ask them, if you like.
- Aiden: You really haven't changed. You always follow your principles.
	Bailey: Don't you?
	Bailey: Except when you're stealing brandy, that is?
	Aiden: I'll have you know that where brandy is concerned, those ARE my principles!
- Aiden: They seem fine with telling your stories.
	Bailey: Only the ones you already know, mostly because you're in them.
Bailey: It's too bad the stars aren't out now. I could use one of your stories.
Aiden: I haven't really told any since you left. You were my only audience.
Bailey: Well that's a waste. You should have found someone.
Aiden: ...
Bailey: ...
Aiden: Why did you come back?
Aiden: I'm... not complaining. I'm glad you did. But what brought you here?
Bailey: It was... partly Ira. They really wanted to see this place.
Bailey: But also for me. To show people that it's okay to change, to grow, to be who you really are.
Bailey: And that there's life beyond the edge of town; people don't get swallowed up and vanish when they leave.
Bailey: And maybe... to find some closure with my family.
Aiden: How'd that go?
- Bailey: Terribly.
	set ELog.Bailey_Parents = 2
	Bailey: They kept calling me by my deadname. And 'he'. And they wouldn't even talk to Ira.
	Bailey: Not that Ira didn't try.
	Aiden: Did Ira even notice they weren't being talked to?
	Bailey: They couldn't not. Ira's awkward but they're not stupid; and they're not used to that kind of reaction from people.
- Bailey: Could have been better.
	set ELog.Bailey_Parents = 1
	Bailey: They called me by my deadname, and "he", about a half dozen times.
	Bailey: They weren't doing it to make a point. But they weren't putting in a lot of effort not to, either.
- Bailey: Could have been worse.
	set ELog.Bailey_Parents = 0
	Bailey: They called me by my deadname, and "he", about a half dozen times.
	Bailey: But they did apologize when they noticed it. So I guess they're trying.
Aiden: "Deadname"?
Bailey: My old name. From before I told them who I am. "Deadname" is what they call it in Iris.
Aiden: "Deadname." That makes sense.
Ira: [i]::huff::[/i]
Ira: [i]::puff::[/i]
Ira: [i]::huff::[/i]
Aiden: Did you catch your squirrel?
Ira: Well... I caught it by the tail!
Ira: But then I thought, "Wait, aren't squirrel tails supposed to be fluffy?"
Ira: I... think it was just a rat. So I let go.
Aiden: You ready to go somewhere else?
Ira: Sure! Where!?
Aiden: Let's see if you can tell me when we get there.

~ big_tree
Ira:  Is this... Is this the TREE?
Aiden: Well, it's A tree. You don't have those in the big city?
Ira: Oh, of course! We have a park that's bigger than this [[whole, entire]] village, not counting the fields! [next]
Ira: But this is THE tree, isn't it? The oak tree where you and Bailey carved your names?!
Aiden: Is there [i]anything[/i] you didn't tell them about?
Bailey: I talked about things that were important to me. [next]
Bailey: And mostly about the good things. And this is both, so. [i]::shrug::
Ira: Can I see where you carved them?
Bailey: We were in the branches when we did it, and it's grown since then. [next]
Bailey: You'll have to climb it if you want to find it.
Ira: It's awfully high...
Aiden: Maybe there'll be squirrels.
Ira: I'm on it! [i]::scoots up the tree::
Bailey: How've [i]you[/i] been?
Aiden: As you see it. Life here doesn't change much.
Bailey: It's a good little town. Better than most of them around.
Aiden: But not better than the city?
Bailey: Iris is... different. And it's better than other cities. [wait = 1.5] [next]
Bailey: At least for people like us.
Aiden: Especially with the parents you had, right?
Bailey: Yeah. Your parents were always one of the things I envied about you.
Bailey: That and getting called "she" as a kid.
Aiden: Ironic, huh? I'd have traded with you there. Neither one ever sat right for me.
Bailey: Yeah. It seems to have worked out for you, though.
Aiden: It's not perfect. There are still a few people here who call me by my... deadname.
Aiden: Most of that stopped after Father Matthew talked to them.
Bailey: I have to go see Matthew and Beatrice later.
Aiden: You're the only one who just calls them by their names. I'll never get used to that.
Bailey: Well I practically grew up in that church. Between them and your parents, they made up for what I didn't find at home.
Aiden: Mind if I come when you go? I haven't seen them in awhile.
Bailey: [i]::gasp::[/i] Have you been skipping church?
Aiden: [i]::blush::[/i] I was never into it as much as you were.
Bailey: [i]::laughs::[/i] I was only kidding. We can go whenever Ira gets back.
Aiden: Unless the squirrels got them.
Bailey: I've seen them get into worse.
::Ira falls out of the tree with a thud::
Ira: "I found your names! AND a squirrel!" [wait = 1] [next]
Ira: The squirrel seemed kind of mad.

~ church
Ira: This is the church? [wait=0.5] It's so... [wait=0.5] small! [wait=1] [next]
Ira: The cathedral in Iris is so big you could fit this whole village inside it!
Aiden: Well, we don't have that many people to fit inside, so it works out.
Bailey: It's not about the size, Ira. It's about the community.
Ira: I know, I know. It's just... different.
Bailey: Let's go say hi.


Father Matthew:  Sister Beatrice! Have you seen my alb?
Sister Beatrice [i](from other room)[/i]: I washed it yesterday...
Sister Beatrice: [i]::entering room::[/i] ...and gave it to you. Folded.
Father Matthew: Are you sure? I don't remember that...
Sister Beatrice: I gave you a ham sandwich at the same time.
Father Matthew: Oh, I remember that sandwich!
Father Matthew: That was a really good sandwich! I ate it at my desk, while I was writing tomorrow's sermon.
Sister Beatrice: Why don't you check by your desk, then?
Father Matthew: [i]::walking into study::[/i] Okay, I'll check, but I--
Father Matthew: ...
Father Matthew: Um. I found it. Thank you, Sister.
::doorbell rings::
Father Matthew: Hello and welcome--
Father Matthew: [b]Bailey?![b] Is that you?
Bailey: Hi, Matthew! It's me.
- Aiden: Um. I'm here too.
	Father Matthew: Oh! I'm sorry, Aiden, of course you are! I didn't mean to ignore you!
	Father Matthew: It's just that Bailey was so unexpected! It's been... how long?
- Aiden: [i]::say nothing::[/i]
	Father Matthew: Oh, and Aiden, you're here as well! I'm sorry, seeing Bailey again just grabbed all of my attention.
	Father Matthew: [i]to Bailey:: [/i] How long has it been?
Father Matthew: And Aiden, it feels like I haven't seen you in a long time, either!
- Aiden: Ah, I'm sorry Father. I've been... forgetting.
- Aiden: I, um. I've been feeling a little sick lately, Father.
- Aiden: We're not all religious fanatics, Father.
Father Matthew: Oh! Oh, no, I didn't mean it like [i]that[/i]! I just mean, around the village.
Father Matthew: [i]::sigh::[/i] I guess I really haven't seen much of anyone lately!
Father Matthew: I've been holed away trying to write tomorrow's sermon.
Father Matthew: The Blessing of Flowers is important, and I always stress about the sermon, but this year is the worst ever!
Father Matthew: I've been banging my head against my desk for weeks, and I just can't make the words come!
Ira: That must have hurt!
Father Matthew: ?
Bailey: Matthew, this is Ira. Ira, this is Father--
Ira: Matthew, I know! He's exactly how I expected him to look, only not quite as tall!
Father Matthew: Um... Thank... you?
Aiden: Ira is a big fan of Ithaca.
Father Matthew: I see.
Father Matthew: ...
Father Matthew: No I don't.
Aiden: It's okay, you just kind of get used to it.
Father Matthew: O...kay. Anwyay. Come in, come in, all of you! What can we do for you?
Bailey: I really just came to see you and Sister Beatrice again.
Father Matthew: I'm so glad you did! And that you brought company!
Father Matthew: [i]::shouts to other room::[/i] Sister! Come quickly, we have visitors!
Father Matthew: Oh, she's going to be so happy to see you! Both of you!
Sister Beatrice: Who is it, Fath--
Sister Beatrice: !!!
Sister Beatrice: BAILEY?!
Sister Beatrice: And Aiden too! Oh, it's been too long! Come here!
::Bailey moves forward for a warm embrace from Sister Beatrice::

Sister Beatrice: You don't have one for me, Aiden?
- Aiden: Of course I do!
	Aiden: [i]::joins hug::[/i]
- Aiden: I, um. I'm getting over a cold.
	Sister Beatrice: [i]::laughs::[/i] It's fine, Aiden: it's an invitation, not a demand!
	Aiden: [i]::smiles::[/i] Thanks for understanding!
- Aiden: No way. Sorry
	Sister Beatrice: [i]::smiles::[/i] That's fine, Aiden! It was meant as an invitation, not a demand!
Ira: Um. What about me?
Sister Beatrice: Oh!
Ira: I'm Ira!
Sister Beatrice: You're a friend of Bailey and Aiden?
Ira: I... think so? [i]::looks at Aiden::

- Aiden: Of course you are!
	Ira: Yay!
- Aiden: Hmm. Okay, why not!
	Ira: Whew!
- Aiden: They're a friend of Bailey.
	Ira: ::looks downcast::

Sister Beatrice: That's good enough for me!
::Ira runs to join hug::
Bailey: It's good to see you, Bea. And you, Matthew.
Father Matthew: I can't believe you're so grown up. You were still a teenager when you left. Sometimes I even still remember you as a little girl.
Bailey: [i]Very[/i] little. You baptized me, remember?
Father Matthew: I'll [i]always[/i] remember that! It was the first baptism I performed after I arrived here. Not that I'll ever tell anyone about it.
Everyone: ???
Father Matthew: A woman's age is her own business. I won't tell on you.
Bailey: I'm not ashamed of my age, Matthew. I'm 25.
Father Matthew: Gosh, I remember 25. Full of possibilities and adventures. In fact, your baptism was one of my adventures! That's almost the age was at that time.
Aiden: We wanted to thank you both. For talking to Bailey's parents.
if DialogSaid.Bailey_Parents == 2
	Bailey: Things haven't much changed, but I really appreciate you trying.
elif DialogSaid.said2 == 1
	Bailey: Things seem a bit better now.
else:
	Bailey: Things are a lot better now.
Sister Beatrice: We're glad to hear that, Aiden. There are a lot of opinions in this town, and we want people to be able to work through them together.
Father Matthew: Yes. We're all a family here.
Bailey: And a better family than a lot of families.
Father Matthew: It's our duty, Bailey. As religious, and as people who love you.
Bailey: ...
Bailey: Alright, Matthew, I'm going to have to go before you make me cry!
Father Matthew: Oh, I'm sorry, I--
Bailey: I'm kidding! I mean, I really am going to cry if you keep this up, but I had to go anyway.
Aiden: Same. I have to get back home by noon to help on the farm.
Father Matthew: That's about... five minutes from now.
Aiden: Oh. I'm not going to make it. Dad's going to want to have words with me.
Sister Beatrice: Father, maybe we can... be a little late to ring the noon bell today?
Father Matthew: [i]::smiles::[/i] I think I've forgotten it already!
Father Matthew: [i]::to Aiden::[/i] I'll remember it in about a quarter hour. Think you'll make it home by then?
Aiden: I can if I cut across Mrs. Azir's field!
Aiden: I'll remind her about church tomorrow as I go through.
Aiden: That way it'll be a visit instead of trespassing!
Bailey: And I have some other places to visit. I will see ALL of you soon!
Sister Beatrice: Thank you for coming up the hill!
Father Matthew: It was good to meet you, Ira!
Ira: It was wonderful to finally meet the two of you!!
::Bailey, Ira, and Aiden leave::
Father Matthew: Well, that was an unexpected pleasure.
Sister Beatrice: Amen!
Father Matthew: [i]::sigh::[/i] And now...
Sister Beatrice: The sermon.
Father Matthew: The sermon.
Sister Beatrice: I thought so. That's why I brought you this.
Father Matthew: A sandwich!
Sister Beatrice: I hope it helps.
Father Matthew: Thank you, sister!
Sister Beatrice: [i]::leaves::
Father Matthew: [i]::sighs, sits at desk::[/i]
::fade out on Father Matthew's study::

~ post_church
set DialogSaid.said1 = false
set DialogSaid.said2 = false
set DialogSaid.said3 = false
set DialogSaid.said4 = false
set DialogSaid.said5 = false
set DialogSaid.said6 = false

Aiden: You said you had to leave. You have someplace to go, or do you want to come with me for lunch?
Ira: Will there be more apple skillet?
Bailey: I'd love to, but we have to go. I have some more people to see before we leave.
Aiden: You're leaving?
Bailey: Well yea. I mean, not for a few days, but when I go again I want to...
Aiden: ...not leave any loose ends?
Bailey: ...
Aiden: Am I loose end?
Bailey: Silly, what do you think?
- Aiden: I think I should be glad I was one of your first stops.
- Aiden: I think you deserve to finally be free of this town.
- Aiden: I think Im going to miss you again.

Bailey: Aiden, I don't want to go back to missing you. They're only a few parts of this town but I ever wanted to see again, and I can count them all on this hand. And you're this one. :: Holds up index finger::
Ira: Is that better or worse than a thumb?
Bailey: ...
Aiden: ...
Ira: It's just that I can see it being either one, because the index finger is important for pointing and we use it to make the number one, but a thumb is used for a thumbs up and also it's opposable...
Bailey: Ira, that's not really the point. The point is that Aiden's--
Bailey: Aiden? Are you okay?
Aiden: I don't know that carriage.  Or the horses. We don't get strange carriages coming through this little town, except sometimes on Market Day, and this isn't Market Day.
Bailey: That's a Church carriage.
Aiden: The church doesn't have a carriage.
Bailey: No. Not the church. The Church. That's an emissary from the Holy City.
Bailey: Even the Cathedral in Iris only gets a visit from one of those every year or two.
Ira: They might just be passing through.
Aiden: Ithaca is the outskirts of the hinterlands. There's nothing on the other side to pass through it [i]to[/i].
Bailey:  It's going toward the church.
Aiden: Someone's getting out.
::The carriage stops in front of the church. A dark figure in a hood and mask steps out, looks about suspiciously, and enters church.::
Aiden: That...
Aiden: That has to be the most sinister way you can go into a church.
Bailey: That was an Inquisitor. I've seen one before, at the Cathedral.
Aiden: Why would one come here?
Ira: Maybe they heard about your stories too?
Bailey: I don't want to think of the stories that would have brought an Inquisitor here.
Bailey: We should go.
Aiden: Yeah, I'm already late.
Bailey: Yeah. That too.


~ aiden_travel_choice
Where does Aiden go next?
- Mrs. Azir's [if DialogSaid.said6 == false]
	set DialogSaid.said6 = true
