~ mrs_azirs
Aiden: Mrs. Azir! Are you home?
Mrs Azir: Aiden! Is that you? I told you kids to stop cutting through my field! You'll scare the crows!
Aiden: I'm not cutting through, Ms. Azir, I came to see you! To remind you that tomorrow's the Blessing of Flowers at church, and remind you to bring your seedlings.
Mrs Azir: Child, at my age I can't carry the number of seedlings I'd need for my sins!
Aiden: Mrs. Azir, you hardly even leave your farm, how many sins could you possibly need to plant flowers for?
Mrs Azir: For a start, sins of wrath every time one of you children comes through my field and bothers my crows!
Mrs Azir: For another thing, the same thing every time one of you asks persnippety questions about my private life like how many sins I can have.
Mrs Azir: My sinnnin' is my own business, and if you think I can't do it at my age you got no idea just how many sins are out there waitin' to happen!
- Aiden: O...kay. Well, I could come and help you carry them if you like.
	[set DialogSaid.said1 = true] [next]
	Mrs Azir: Hmm. Carryin' the flowers for another's sins. Why, that sounds almost scriptural. Alrighty, then, thank you Aiden.
	Mrs Azir: I know I can get persnippety myself, but you always were a good... er, child. You come by here on your way to church tomorrow and I'll have my flowers ready.
	Mrs Azir: And that way when you cut across, it won't be tresspassin', innit?
	Aiden: ::blushes:: You got it, Mrs. Azir.
- Aiden: Why don't you just bring seeds, then? They're tiny.
	Mrs Azir: Seeds for sins? At my age, I don't expect to be around long enough for 'em to grow up and flower.
	Aiden: Well, we could always put them on your grave. Besides, my Daddy says you're probably going outlive us all.
	Mrs Azir: Well, your Daddy was always a pessimist. But it would certainly be a powerful lot of flowers to remember me by...
	Mrs Alrighty, then. I'll bring a pocket full of teff grains. I'll prbably be able to sow a field with 'em, you can bake my funeral bread with it.
Mrs Azir: Get on home now, your Daddy'll most likely be expectin' you by noon bell. If there were ever a man of habit, it's him.
if  DialogSaid.said1 == true
	Aiden: ::grins:: You always know the score, Mrs. Azir. I'll see you in the morning!
	::Aiden leaves::
else:
	Aiden: ::smiles:: You always know the score, Mrs. Azir.
	::Aiden leaves::
=> aiden_travel_choice

~ home_after_church1
if DialogSaid.Aiden_Late_for_Home == true
	Samwell: Well, well. Tryin' a sneak in after the bell? That sort of thinkin' is why I never had no truck with school!
	Aiden: I'm sorry, Daddy, but something really bad happened at the church.
	Samwell: If'n it's on fire, that shoulda been the first thing out yer mouth. If it's anything else, Father Matthew can handle it.
	Aiden: That just it, Daddy, I don't think he can. It looked bad to me and Bailey seemed even more worried about it.
	Samwell: You let him handle the church and you handle the cowcrap in the barn. I ain't too proud to admit my back ain't in for it no more.
	Aiden: I'll do it dooble time to make up for getting back late.
	Samwell: I [i]know[/i] you will, child. The whole reason I can be so rough on you is I know you know you don't deserve it.
	Aiden: Daddy I... think that was the nicest thing you've ever said to me?
	Samwell: Don't get used to it. I'm a crotchety old man, it's my whole thing. ::leaves::
else:
	::church bell rings::
	Samwell: Well you made it.
	Samwell: Feels like the morning stretched itself out a bit fer ya. But I suppose if it's alright wi' God, it's alright wi' me.
	Aiden: Yeah... speaking of that, Daddy... I think there's something bad going on at the church. Bailey thought so too and she knows more about it than I do.
	Samwell: If'n it's on fire, that shoulda been the first thing out yer mouth. If it's anything else, Father Matthew can handle it.
	Aiden: That just it, Daddy, I don't think he can. He got a visit from an inquisitor, from the Holy City.
	Samwell: Well he can inquisit all he wants, he won;'t find anything against Father. He's as fine a man as any who isn't head of this household. I can't imagine him doing anything wrong.
	Aiden: I hope you're right, Daddy.
	Samwell: Tell you what; I ain't been regular at the church for a year or twelve, but I've always like the Flower Party...
	Aiden: Blessing of Flowers, Daddy.
	Samwell: Wha'ever. Always enjoyed it. I'll come along tomorrow and I'll put in a good word for Matthew with the inquisitor.
	Aiden: I'm not sure how much the inquisitor will--
	Samwell: The name of Samwell of Samwell's Farm is known further than you know, child. Also, you know I've al'ays has a persuasive way about me. That's why yer Ma married me.
	Cora (from other room): He had more hair then, mind.
	Samwell: I've ever [i]quality[/i], woman, not [i]quantity[/i]! Silver's worth more than sable, that's all!
	Samwell: now, you stop yer frettin'; about and go much out the crap from the barn. Them cow's been eatin' well.

