~ post_inquisitor
Sister Beatrice: We're sorry, Aiden. Father Matthew was--
Father Matthew: Don't try to shield me from my actions, Sister.
Father Matthew: Aiden, I'm sorry. I... know that was unexpected and hurtful.
Aiden: Both of those, yes.
Father Matthew: I... was trying to protect you.
- Aiden: I understand.
- Aiden: Don't protect me that way ever again.
	Father Matthew: ...
	Father Matthew: Alright. I won't. And I [i]am[/i] sorry.
- Aiden: I think you were trying to protect yourself.
	Father Matthew: I'm trying to protect this entire town.
Sister Beatrice: Aiden, we would never want to hurt you. But the Inquisitor... would.
Sister Beatrice: I don't think you understand how strict the Holy City can be about these things.
Father Matthew: And that's my fault. I've tried to shield this town from... the worst of the Church. I should have taught the best while preparing you for the rest.
Sister Beatrice: It wouldn't work that way, Matthew, you know it.
Father Matthew: [i]Sister[/i].
Sister Beatrice: [i]Father[/i]. Yes, I'm sorry. But you know it wouldn't work that way.
Aiden: I don't know what you're talking about. Who was that and why are you both acting scared?
Sister Beatrice: Because that was a person to be scared of, Aiden.
Father Matthew: Inquisitor Malachai was sent by the Church to investigate reports of heresy.
Aiden: So? You're afraid you're going to get framed as heretics?
Sister Beatrice: ...
Father Matthew: No, Aiden. We're afraid...
Father Matthew: ...because we [i]are[/i] heretics.
Sister Beatrice: You should go now, Aiden. It... may not be safe for you here while it Inquisitor is visiting.
- Aiden: It sounds like it's not safe for you, either.
	Father Matthew: Maybe. The difference is that this is something that we knew might come. We made our decisions about the truths we would teach long before you were born.
- Aiden: What have you brought to this town?
	Father Matthew: I think that we brought truth, Aiden. I hope that we brought love, and understanding.
- Aiden: Is anyone safe?
	Father Matthew: I think that most people are. At worst, they'll be able to say they were misled by us. At leat, the people who the Church doesn't see as... different.
	Aiden: Different like me. Like Bailey.
	Father Matthew: ... Yes. And Ira, probably. A few others. Old Armory, for one.
	Sister Beatrice: Andrea Weaver told me last week after mass that they want to be called Andrew.
	Aiden: They're only five years old. The Church wouldn't hurt them, would they?
	Father Matthew: Physically? Maybe not. But they could torture a child like that without touching them at all.
	Aiden: I...
	Aiden. Yes.
Sister Beatrice: You should go now, Aiden. We have to get ready for tomorrow. Maybe we can get satisfy the Inquisitor that there's no problem.
Aiden: I just made that harder, didn't I?
Father Matthew: You spoke your truth, Aiden. That's all God would ask of you. I can't ask anything more.
Father Matthew: Sister Beatrice is right, We need to work on a plan for tomorrow. You're already late for home, aren't you?
Aiden: I... guess so...
Sister Beatrice: It's brave of you to want to help, Aiden. We're so proud of you. But there isn't anything you can do here now.
Aiden: I'll...
Aiden: Take care, both of you.
Father Matthew: Go with God.
::Aiden leaves::

