~ matthew_sermon
[i]::the next morning::[/i]
Father Matthew: Today is the Blessing of Flowers.
Inquisitor: ::quietly enters the church::
Father Matthew: ::rustles notes:: Er. Forgive me.
Father Matthew: As I said--
Father Matthew: Today is--
Father Matthew: ::Father Matthew look up at the Inquisitor...::
Father Matthew: ::...down at this notes...::
Father Matthew: ::...up at the Inquisitor...::
Father Matthew: ::...and tears his notes in two::
Sister Beatrice: ::eyes go wide.::
Ira: ::whispers:: What's he doing?
Bailey: [i]Shh![/i]
Father Matthew: As I was saying...Today is the Blessing of Flowers.
Father Matthew: It is one of the oldest of holy days... at least, one of the oldest that the Church still observes.
Father Matthew: There are of course others that the church has changed its mind about...
Father Matthew: We no longer chant the Litany of Liberation, or fast throughout the Month of Revelation.
Father Matthew: We don't hear about the Month of Mercy or think up questions for the Celebration of Reason.
Father Matthew: And of course we never, ever talk about the Festival of Libido!
Father Matthew: Those things are gone now. Heresies. We do still have the Week of Wrath. Once just a single day of atonement.
Father Matthew: And of course, we still have the Blessing of Flowers.
Father Matthew: The day when we contemplate our sins, and plant flowers for them, that their ugliness may bring forth beauty in the world.
Father Matthew: My... friends. I have been guilty of sin.
Crowd: ::sudden muttering::
Father Matthew: It's only now that I have realized that I have been guilty of... hubris.
Father Matthew: I had... forgotten what faith is. But this morning, I am reminded.
Father Matthew: I have spent weeks trying to write a sermon for today's celebration.
Father Matthew: I sat at my desk, pen in hand, bent over a sheet of paper...
Father Matthew: Not always the same sheet. Often I wrote a few words, then crossed them out. I went through many pages that way.
Father Matthew: I kept trying to make the words come. I prayed for the words to come. I read past sermons, trying to make... the words... come.
Father Matthew: Last night, I finally forced words onto the page. They looked wrong there...
Father Matthew: ...but we have to do, what we have to do. That is duty. Right?
Father Matthew: But it was [i]not[/i]. It was not my duty, as your priest, to make... the words... come.
Father Matthew: My duty is to open myself to the Spririt, and let it speak through me.
Father Matthew: The Spirit has shown me. The Spirit speaks through me now.
Father Matthew: You've heard it said that without love, our works, however noble, are nothing.
Father Matthew: You may have even heard it said that, without love, WE are nothing.
Father Matthew: But the Spirit says more.
Father Matthew: Without love... GOD is nothing.
Crowd: ::gasps::
Father Matthew: For what would such a god be? What is a god who controls...
Father Matthew: ...who commands...
Father Matthew: ...who condemns our sins...
Father Matthew: ...if that god sets one person's love above another's.
Father Matthew: The only thing worse is a god... who [i]forbids[/i] love.
Father Matthew: THAT is true heresy.
Father Matthew: God [i]is[/i], and must [i]be[/i], love.
Father Matthew: For without love, we are not worthy of God.
Father Matthew: But without love, [i]God[/i] would not be worthy... of [i]us[/i].
Inquisitor: ENOUGH!
Inquisitor: ::to his guards:: Take him away!
Aiden: !!!
Bailey: ::whispers:: Wait!
Inquisitor: ::to crowd:: I am Knight Inquisitor Malachai. I have been sent to this place by the Holy Church to investigate rumors of heresy. Rumors that I now see are well founded.
Inquisitor Malachai: I am replacing Father Matthew as head priest of this church, effective immediately. During my investigation, this church will remain open from dawn until duskm, that all may come an make confession.
Inquisitor Malachai: I foresee the need for many confessions.
Inquisitor Malachai: This mass is ended. Go now, and serve the Lord.
=> after_matthew_sermon

~ after_matthew_sermon
Bailey: I can't believe he did that.
- Aiden: I didn't realize he was that brave.
	Bailey: I... always thought of him as brave, but... not like that.
- Aiden: I didn't realize he was that reckless.
	Bailey: I don't think it was recklessness. I think it was something else.
	Aiden: What? Courage?
	Bailey: That too? But I meant... what he said. The Spirit speaking to him.
- Aiden: I didn't realize he was that stupid.
	Bailey: That wasn't stupidity.
	Aiden: What would you call it? He just gave the Inquisitor everything he needed to take over the church.
	Bailey: He spoke the truth in the face of power.
	Aiden: That's not going to do any of us any good now.
	Ira: I don't get it. What did he say that was wrong?
	Bailey: He said a lot, Ira.
	Aiden: He said that love was more important than God.
	Bailey: And he said that God could be wrong.
Aiden: What's going to happen to him?
Bailey: I'm not sure. If he stands accused of heresy, there will have to be a trial. The Inquisitor can't discipline a priest directly; he'll have to be brought to the Holy City.
Aiden: What about people who aren't priests?
Ira: He can appoint a jury in the case of laity.
Aiden: How do you know that?
Ira: My father studied to be a priest when he was younger. He never took his orders, but he knew a lot about the Inquisitors.
Ira: He said that they were the [i]reason[/i] he never took his orders.
Bailey: Did... you talk to the Inquisitor, Aiden?
Aiden: What? Why?
Bailey: Because he seems to be coming toward us.
Aiden: We should go.
Bailey: I think it's too late. Running is just going to make them hunt us down.
::Inquisitor Malachai stops as Samwell puts himself in his path.::
Samwell: Hey, Father Inquisitor, I need to speak with you.
Inquisitor Malachai: ::surprised and annoyed::  You may call me Inquisitor Malachai. And now is not the time--
Samwell: But yer actin' preist, ain't ya? You just said so. So you're a Father.
Samwell: An' I'm a father too, just the more physical, less spiritual, sort. And I gotta tell you, Dad to Dad, you're makin' a mistake on this one.
Samwell: Father Matthew, he's as good a man a`s there is who ain't--
Inquisitor Malachai: I will be taking interviews later as part of my investigation, right now I--
Samwell: ::ahem:: I should tell you, Father, that my name, which I've not yet mentioned, not wantin' to abuse my reputation, is [i]Samwell[/i].
Inquisitor Malachai: ...
Samwell: Of [i]Samwell's Farm[/i]!
Guard: ::whispers to Inquisitor Malachai::
Bailey: Okay, [i]now[/i] I think we should go.
Aiden: Yeah, good plan.
::Aiden, Bailey, and Ira leave::
Inquisitor Malachai: [i]::to Guard::[/i] What do you mean you've heard of him? That has nothing to do with anything! [i]He[/i] has nothing to do with anything! Get him out of my way!
Inquisitor Malachai: [i]::resumes moving toward Aiden and company:: [/i]
Mrs Azir: What about the flowers?!
Inquisitor Malachai: What? How did this woman get in front of--
Mrs Azir: It's the Blessing. [wait = 1] Of. [wait = 1] The Flowers.
Mrs Azir: You can't just end the Mass without one flower bein' blessed! I am an old woman, I got a lot of sinnin' to take care of!
Inquisitor Malachai: You can deal with those at Confession!
Mrs Azir: Nah, nah! I ain't havin' my sin's just up an' vanish! It's gotta be flowers!
Inquisitor Malachai: For your information, the High Lictor is expected to eliminate the Blessing of Flowers from the liturgical calendar at the next Conclave.
Inquisitor Malachai: It is a heretical tradition that was brought into the church in a misguided attempt to woo pagans to the Church.
Mrs Azir: They're takin' away the flowers!? You tryin' to get folks to just stay home?!

::This is as far as has been written::
=> END!
